    <p class="italic">Note: Answer the two following exercises. Accuracy in calculations and clarity of reasoning are essential.</p>

    <!-- EXERCISE 1: ELECTROMAGNETIC INDUCTION - ROTATING COIL (10 pts) -->
    <div class="exercise">
        <div class="exercise-head">
            <span>Exercise 1: Rotating Coil in a Magnetic Field</span>
            <span>(10 points)</span>
        </div>
        <p>A flat circular coil consists of \(N = 100\) turns, each of area \(S = 50 \, \text{cm}^2\). The coil is connected to a resistor of resistance \(R = 10 \, \Omega\). The total resistance of the coil is \(r_c = 2 \, \Omega\). The coil is placed in a uniform magnetic field \(\vec{B}\) of magnitude \(B = 0.2 \, \text{T}\). The coil rotates around a diameter perpendicular to \(\vec{B}\) at a constant angular velocity \(\omega = 10\pi \, \text{rad/s}\).</p>
        
        <div class="figure-box">
            <svg width="400" height="180" viewBox="0 0 400 180">
                <!-- Uniform B Field Arrows -->
                <line x1="20" y1="40" x2="100" y2="40" stroke="#ccc" marker-end="url(#arrowB)" />
                <line x1="20" y1="90" x2="100" y2="90" stroke="#ccc" marker-end="url(#arrowB)" />
                <line x1="20" y1="140" x2="100" y2="140" stroke="#ccc" marker-end="url(#arrowB)" />
                <text x="30" y="30" fill="gray" font-weight="bold">B</text>

                <!-- Rotating Coil -->
                <ellipse cx="200" cy="90" rx="30" ry="70" fill="none" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" />
                <line x1="200" y1="10" x2="200" y2="170" stroke="black" stroke-dasharray="5,5" />
                <text x="185" y="15" font-size="12">Axis</text>
                
                <!-- Normal Vector n -->
                <line x1="200" y1="90" x2="260" y2="60" stroke="blue" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arrowN)" />
                <text x="265" y="60" fill="blue" font-weight="bold">n</text>

                <!-- Angle theta -->
                <path d="M 230 90 A 30 30 0 0 0 225 75" fill="none" stroke="red" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <text x="235" y="85" fill="red">&theta;</text>

                <defs>
                    <marker id="arrowB" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="0" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                        <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="#ccc" />
                    </marker>
                    <marker id="arrowN" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="0" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                        <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="blue" />
                    </marker>
                </defs>
            </svg>
            <p class="italic">Figure 1: Coil rotating in a uniform magnetic field.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">1)</span> Let \(\theta = (\vec{B}, \vec{n})\) be the angle between the magnetic field and the normal to the coil. At \(t = 0\), \(\theta = 0\).
            <div class="sub-q">a) Express \(\theta\) as a function of time \(t\).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Show that the magnetic flux \(\Phi\) through the coil at any time \(t\) is: \(\Phi(t) = 0.1 \cos(10\pi t)\) (Wb).</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">2)</span> Determine the expression of the induced electromotive force \(e(t)\). Calculate its maximum value \(E_{max}\).</div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">3)</span> Calculate the instantaneous induced current \(i(t)\) in the circuit.</div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">4)</span> The mechanical power required to maintain the rotation is dissipated by the Joule effect in the circuit.
            <div class="sub-q">a) Express the instantaneous power \(P(t)\) dissipated by the Joule effect.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Calculate the average power \(P_{avg}\) over one period. (Recall: Average of \(\sin^2(\alpha)\) is \(1/2\)).</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">5)</span> If the rotation speed is doubled, how are the maximum e.m.f and the average power affected? Justify.</div>
    </div>

    <!-- EXERCISE 2: SELF-INDUCTION - ENERGY AND VOLTAGE (10 pts) -->
    <div class="exercise">
        <div class="exercise-head">
            <span>Exercise 2: Energy Storage and Circuit Interruption</span>
            <span>(10 points)</span>
        </div>
        <p>A circuit is composed of a generator of e.m.f \(E = 10 \, \text{V}\), a coil of inductance \(L = 0.5 \, \text{H}\) and internal resistance \(r = 5 \, \Omega\), a rheostat of resistance \(R_h\), and a switch \(K\).</p>

        <div class="figure-box">
            <svg width="500" height="180" viewBox="0 0 500 180">
                <!-- DC Source (Cleaned up lines) -->
                <!-- Top wire to source -->
                <line x1="50" y1="40" x2="50" y2="80" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <!-- Positive Plate -->
                <line x1="35" y1="80" x2="65" y2="80" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" /> 
                <!-- Negative Plate -->
                <line x1="42" y1="90" x2="58" y2="90" stroke="black" stroke-width="5" />
                <!-- Bottom wire from source -->
                <line x1="50" y1="90" x2="50" y2="140" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <text x="20" y="88" font-weight="bold">E</text>
                
                <!-- Main Loop Top and Bottom -->
                <line x1="50" y1="40" x2="120" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <line x1="50" y1="140" x2="400" y2="140" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Switch K -->
                <circle cx="120" cy="40" r="3" fill="black" />
                <line x1="120" y1="40" x2="160" y2="15" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" />
                <circle cx="170" cy="40" r="3" fill="black" />
                <text x="135" y="10" font-weight="bold">K</text>
                <line x1="170" y1="40" x2="220" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Coil (L, r) -->
                <path d="M 220 40 Q 225 25 230 40 Q 235 25 240 40 Q 245 25 250 40 Q 255 25 260 40 Q 265 25 270 40" fill="none" stroke="blue" stroke-width="2" />
                <text x="225" y="65" fill="blue" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">(L, r)</text>
                <line x1="270" y1="40" x2="400" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Rheostat Rh (Cleaned up connections) -->
                <line x1="400" y1="40" x2="400" y2="70" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <!-- The box -->
                <rect x="385" y="70" width="30" height="40" fill="none" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" />
                <!-- Bottom wire connection: starts exactly at y=110 -->
                <line x1="400" y1="110" x2="400" y2="140" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                
                <!-- Arrow for Rheostat -->
                <line x1="375" y1="115" x2="425" y2="65" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowRh)" />
                <text x="430" y="95" font-weight="bold">R<sub>h</sub></text>

                <defs>
                    <marker id="arrowRh" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="4" refY="4" orient="auto">
                        <polygon points="0 0, 8 4, 0 8" fill="black" />
                    </marker>
                </defs>
            </svg>
            <p class="italic">Figure 2: Circuit diagram for RL study.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">1) Establishment of the current.</span> The rheostat is adjusted so that the total resistance of the circuit is \(R_{total} = 25 \, \Omega\). The switch \(K\) is closed at \(t = 0\).
            <div class="sub-q">a) Define the self-inductance \(L\) of a coil.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Establish the differential equation for the voltage \(u_R(t)\) across the resistive part (Rheostat + internal resistance).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">c) Calculate the value of the current \(I_0\) in the steady state.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">d) Calculate the energy \(W_m\) stored in the coil at steady state.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">2) Opening of the circuit.</span> The steady state being reached, the switch \(K\) is suddenly opened.
            <div class="sub-q">a) What happens to the energy stored in the coil?</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) A voltmeter connected across the terminals of the switch \(K\) indicates a very high voltage during the opening. Explain the origin of this overvoltage.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">3) Role of a Diode.</span> To protect the circuit, a diode is connected in parallel with the coil (Freewheeling diode).
            <div class="sub-q">a) Sketch the modified diagram.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Qualitatively explain how the diode prevents the overvoltage at the switch terminals.</div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MARKING SCHEME SECTION -->
    <div class="marking-scheme">
        <div class="header">
            <h1>MARKING SCHEME (BARÈME)</h1>
        </div>
        
        <h3 class="bold">Exercise 1: Rotating Coil (10 pts)</h3>
        <table class="scheme-table">
            <tr><th>Q</th><th>Expected Answer / Distribution of Points</th><th class="pts">Points</th></tr>
            <tr><td>1.a</td><td>\(\theta = \omega t = 10\pi t\) (rad).</td><td class="pts">0.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.b</td><td>\(\Phi = N B S \cos(\theta) = 100 \cdot 0.2 \cdot (50 \times 10^{-4}) \cdot \cos(10\pi t) = 0.1 \cos(10\pi t)\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td>\(e = -d\Phi/dt = -[0.1 \cdot (-10\pi) \cdot \sin(10\pi t)] = \pi \sin(10\pi t)\). \(E_{max} = \pi \approx 3.14 \, \text{V}\).</td><td class="pts">2.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>\(i(t) = e / (R + r_c) = \pi \sin(10\pi t) / 12 \approx 0.26 \sin(10\pi t) \, \text{A}\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.a</td><td>\(P(t) = (R+r_c) \cdot i^2 = 12 \cdot [(\pi/12) \sin(10\pi t)]^2 = (\pi^2 / 12) \sin^2(10\pi t)\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.b</td><td>\(P_{avg} = (\pi^2 / 12) \cdot (1/2) = \pi^2 / 24 \approx 0.41 \, \text{W}\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>If \(\omega' = 2\omega\), then \(E'_{max} = 2 E_{max}\) (since \(e \propto \omega\)). Average power \(\propto E_{max}^2 \propto \omega^2\), so power quadruples.</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3 class="bold" style="margin-top:20px;">Exercise 2: Energy Storage (10 pts)</h3>
        <table class="scheme-table">
            <tr><th>Q</th><th>Expected Answer / Distribution of Points</th><th class="pts">Points</th></tr>
            <tr><td>1.a</td><td>Inductance is the property of a circuit to oppose changes in current by inducing an e.m.f.</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.b</td><td>\(E = L(di/dt) + R_{tot}i\). Since \(u_R = R_{tot}i \implies i = u_R/R_{tot}\). \((L/R_{tot})du_R/dt + u_R = E\).</td><td class="pts">2.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.c</td><td>Steady state: \(di/dt = 0 \implies I_0 = E / R_{tot} = 10 / 25 = 0.4 \, \text{A}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.d</td><td>\(W_m = \frac{1}{2} L I_0^2 = 0.5 \cdot 0.5 \cdot (0.4)^2 = 0.04 \, \text{J} = 40 \, \text{mJ}\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.a</td><td>Energy must be dissipated. Usually appears as heat in a spark or across resistances.</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.b</td><td>Sudden break \(\implies dt \to 0 \implies |di/dt|\) is extremely high. \(u_L = -L di/dt\) becomes huge.</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.a</td><td>Drawing: Diode in parallel with coil, cathode towards the positive terminal.</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.b</td><td>Provides a closed path for current after switch opens, allowing current to decrease gradually.</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
        </table>
    </div>
